 collection consider how distinct habits of writing took root among specific communities in Italy between the early Middle Ages and the eve of the Renaissance.In examining how ideological concerns helped give shape to strategies of writing and how forms of communication influenced cultural developments, these case studies assess a wide range of texts, including legal treatises, saintly biographies, rhetorical handbooks, and vernacular poetry. As a whole, the collection makes the case for combining abstract analyses such as textual theory and intellectual history with more technical specialties such as editing and codicology. Rather than approaching pre-modern Italian textuality as something uniform, Textual Cultures of Medieval Italy engages with its fascinating plurality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh1 aBendinelli Predelli, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoschetto, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleinhenz, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLepsius, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoirel, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobins, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSafran, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWitt, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269460640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442694606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442694606.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN